title: The Rape of Europa, from the Suite of Late Wood-Block Prints

thumbnail.alt_text: A work made of wood-block print in black ink on thin, ivory japanese paper, laid face down on ivory wove paper (recto); wood-block print in yellow ocher ink on ivory wove paper (verso).

medium_display: Wood-block print in black ink on thin, ivory Japanese paper, laid face down on ivory wove paper (recto); wood-block print in yellow ocher ink on ivory wove paper (verso)
publication_history:
Marcel Guérin, L'Oeuvre Gravé de Gauguin (Paris, 1927), n.p., cat. 65.

The Art Institute of Chicago, Gauguin Prints (Chicago, 1959), n.p. (ill.).

Richard S. Field, Paul Gauguin: The Paintings of the First Voyage to Tahiti (Cambridge, Mass, 1963), diss., n.p., fig. 60 (ill.). 

Elizabeth Mongan, Eberhard W. Kornfeld, and Harold Joachim, Paul Gauguin: Catalogue Raisonné of His Prints (Bern, 1988), pp. 186-187, no. 47 (ill.)

Bernard Denvir, Paul Gauguin: The Search for Paradise, Letters from Brittany and the South Seas (London, 1992), pp. 132-133 (ill.).

Anna Maria Damigella, Paul Gauguin: La vita e l'opera (Milan, 1997), p. 232 (ill.).
exhibition_history:
The Art Institute of Chicago, "Gauguin: Paintings, Drawings, Prints, Sculpture," February 12-March 29, 1959, p. 88, cat. 179; traveled to the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, April 21-May 31, 1959.

Munich, Haus der Kunst, "Paul Gauguin," April 1-May 29, 1960, p. 36, cat. 198, pl. 89 (ill.).

Vienna, Österreichische Galerie im Oberen Belvedere, "Paul Gauguin," June 7-July 31, 1960, p. 46, cat. 101, pl. 29.

Washington D.C., National Gallery of Art, "The Art of Paul Gauguin," 1988, p. 437, cat. 233 (ill); shown only at The Art Institute of September 17-December 11, 1988.

The Art Institute of Chicago, "Gauguin: Artist as Alchemist",  June 25 - September 10, 2017, pp. 17, 41, 42, 292, 304, 305, cat. 246, cat. by Gloria Groom, et. al., traveled to Paris, Réunion des musées nationaux - Grand Palais, October 9, 2017 - January 21, 2018.
provenance_text: Maurice Denis (1870-1943), Paris {Kornfeld 1988].  Sold by Daniel Sickles, Paris, to the Art Institute, 1949.

input: The Rape of Europa, from the Suite of Late Wood-Block Prints
